    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-01-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-01-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="814"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d814">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00114A Pacific War/297: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harrison</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-01-13">January 13,
                            1943</date>.<lb/>[Received January 13—11:59 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>285. American interests—prisoners of war—China. Department’s 2761, December
                        7;<note n="85" xml:id="d814fn85">
                        <ref target="frus1942v01#pg_830">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1942, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 830</ref>.</note> Legation’s 6036,
                    December 21.<note n="86" xml:id="d814fn86">Not printed; it reported that the
                        contents of No. 2761 had been transmitted to Intercroixrouge on December 8,
                        1942 (740.00114A Pacific War/262).</note> Intercroixrouge, Geneva, writes
                    January 11.</p>
                <pb facs="0968" n="956" xml:id="pg_956"/>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“Instructed Zindel, our delegate Hong Kong, visit four American aviators
                        reported prisoners Canton. Unfortunately visit impossible as activity
                        delegate now confined Hong Kong exclusively. Paravicini,<note n="87"
                            xml:id="d814fn87">F. Paravicini, International Red Cross Committee
                            delegate to Japan.</note> Tokyo, requested intervene Japanese
                        authorities obtain authorization visit.”<note n="88" xml:id="d814fn88">In
                            telegram No. 1201, February 20 (740.00114A Pacific War/333), the
                            Minister in Switzerland reported that the aviators were interned at
                            Shanghai. In telegram No. 2102, April 3 (740.00114A Pacific War/390), he
                            stated that a representative of the Intercroixrouge on March 24 had
                            visited the aviators in a prisoners-of-war camp near Shanghai where they
                            were reported as being in good health and treated the same as other
                            prisoners of war.</note>
                    </p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harrison</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
